'''Gregg McClymont''' (born 3 June 1976) is a [[Scottish Labour Party|Labour Party]] [[politician]], who has been the [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East (UK Parliament constituency)|Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East]] since [[United Kingdom general election, 2010|2010]].

==Background and personal life==
Born and brought up in [[Cumbernauld]], he attended Kildrum Primary School and [[Cumbernauld High School]] from 1981 until 1993. He read History at the [[University of Glasgow]], graduating in 1997, the year when he was also chair of [[Scottish Labour Students]], before winning the Thouron Scholarship to study at the [[University of Pennsylvania]]. Returning to Britain, he did a further History PhD and became a teaching fellow at [[St. Hugh's College, Oxford]].<ref>[http://www.sthughs.ox.ac.uk St Hugh's College, Oxford] Retrieved May 7th, 2010</ref>

==Political life==
He was selected to replace outgoing Labour MP [[Rosemary McKenna]] to fight the seat of [[Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East (UK Parliament constituency)|Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East]] at the [[United Kingdom general election, 2010|2010 general election]]. He won the seat with a 13,755 majority and over 57% of the votes cast.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/nol/shared/election2010/results/constituency/812.stm
|accessdate=7 May 2010 | work=BBC News | title=BBC NEWS <U+2013> Election 2010 <U+2013> Cumbernauld, Kilsyth & Kirkintilloch East}}</ref>
In parliament, McClymont sat on the House of Commons [[Select committee (Westminster system)|select committees]] on science and technology, and business, innovation and skills; and held the post of [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to shadow Secretary of State for Scotland [[Ann McKechin]]. In early 2011, he moved on to the Labour front bench as an assistant whip.<ref>[http://www.cumbernauld-news.co.uk/news/local-headlines/ed_promotes_mp_gregg_1_1478643 Ed promotes MP Gregg] ''Cumbernauld News'', March 2nd, 2011</ref>

